metadata.name: Downpour Noir #22
metadata.description:
A #genuary32nd project.
A hot summer downpour in an oppressive city.

My method for Genuary was to read the prompt for the next day before going to bed, sleeping on it, and then try to quickly find an interesting idea with my morning coffee.

The prompt for Day 19 was "Black and White". My mind went to the high-contrast style of comic-book writer and artist Frank Miller, specifically "Sin City" and "The Dark Knight Returns" and their heavy film-noir influences. The result can be found here : https://ulucode.com/genuary2023/19/

This project is a more polished version of my work that day with a few additional features.

The intended output is what first appears, but in the spirit of Genuary, you can explore and experiment with the controls provided to get creative, but also see under the hood.
The camera is left free, so you can change the point of view.
Here are the camera controls ( mobile in parenthesis ) :
- Mouse left click and drag (Touch drag) to rotate.
- Mouse Right and drag (Two fingers drag) to pan.
- Mouse Wheel/Middle (Pinch) to zoom

/// Press SPACE (or Double Tap on mobile) to show/hide the MENU. ///

In this MENU you can :

- Adjust the anti-aliasing quality : mostly for the animation and camera manipulations. Default is "medium". Try reducing the quality if the animation is choppy. Set it to "ideal" for optimal quality.
- Aspect ratio : you can change the desired aspect ratio from the default "poster" to "window", in which case the piece resizes itself to fill the window in which it is displayed. Useful if you want to capture in other formats.
- Animated : toggle to start/stop the animation
- Display frame : toggle to hide/show the comic-like frame
- Display stats : toggle to display a small FPS counter in the top left.

- Export : choose the resolution and press the "Export capture" button to export a PNG of what is currently displayed. Warning : large resolutions can take a few seconds and weigh around 300Mo. This is the recommended method if you want CLEAN graphic files.

NFT License

Runs on Three.js : https://threejs.org/
GUI uses lil-gui : https://www.npmjs.com/package/lil-gui

metadata.name: Shift #29
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm honing the power of vertical displacement.

How simple may a generative algorithm be while simultaneously staying diverse enough for each art piece to be truly unique? Shift is the result of an exploration into this space, basing its existence on two principles — dissection and vertical shifting. Each variable in this art engine has been meticulously weighted, giving rise to high diversity and the possibility of epic combinations. 

Shift is a series of 888 unique pieces.

############

Display resolution is 1000x1400. Press ’s’ (in live mode) to generate a 6000x8400 hi-res image. This may take a while to generate depending on your hardware.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: Skravert #2
metadata.description:
‘Skravert’ - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‘The act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area’.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: Punktwelt #216
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press ’s’ to save a png. Press ’4’ to export a high resolution png. Press ’8’ to export a very high resolution png. Press ’e’ to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: We Are Alone Together #71
metadata.description:
We meander through the flows of life, alone but together. This experience — an ultimately solitary one — is communicated but never truly shared. Our consciousnesses live in a perpetual separated state, alone but together.

############

Display resolution scales with window size. Press ’h’ (in live mode) to generate a 6000x7500 hi-res image. This may take a few seconds to generate depending on your hardware. Press ‘d’ to redraw the artwork.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: Automatic #481
metadata.description:
Cellular automata is fascinating :) Applications ranging from physics and biology to modeling and architecture, with artistic and aesthetic representation always following along. Perfect example for emergence, how simple even byte-size rules result in complex structures, forming patterns and unpredictable behaviors...

This one is simple, 1d elementary cellular automata and the 256 rules as the foundation, where each iteration consists of the following elements: base rules - 3 are selected and allocated into the start row compositions, a set of shapes is assigned to a grid of various sizes. Occasionally, dynamic rule set is added - where a rule is randomly transformed into another random rule on a random row of the grid. A vertical or horizontal alignment of the grid is chosen an a color set assigned. Sometimes, a simple 2d noise is applied to lighten (or well, darken) things a bit. The grid is finite and confined by the amount of cells in a row and amount of rows fitting the canvas given cell size.

The properties are recorded as features, more as a reference to the building blocks, rather then rarity indication. Probably be best viewed in live mode :)

Pressing 's' in live mode will save the png of the output.

metadata.name: Komposite #22
metadata.description:
Celebrating Genuary 2023, Komposite is a collection exploring minimalism and bringing together few smaller building blocks to build up a more complex and interesting composite effect. The project is an exploration of patterns, shapes, and composition, hoping to build up on these in the future. Happy Genuary :)

Press 's' in live mode to save the output in png format.

Press '2', '3' in live mode to save higher resolution output in png format (may take a moment).

metadata.name: In Between #1
metadata.description:
In Between

Genuary is an artificially generated month of time where we build code that makes beautiful things, with 31 prompts to base your code art off. Genuary 2023 took place during the month of January 2023. Afterwards, as it happens, comes Genuary 32nd. This is an imaginary week, during which we develop one of our Genuary pieces into a 32 edition "not very long"-form generative project on fx(hash).

My Genuary 32nd project is based on Genuary 22nd: Shadows, the design of which again was based on the "art deco" pattern from day 20.

The patterns form a grid-like fence structure, dividing the space and creating an infinite cage. Light coming from the outside casts stark shadows on the floor. Several variations on halftoning techniques are used to portray tone, occasionally destroying depth perception into an abstract interplay of form.

The code of this piece has been diminished into a mere 3397 characters.

You can use the URL-parameter &m=2 as a resolution multiplier, to render images larger than your screen.

(c) 2023 by Piter Pasma. https://piterpasma.nl

metadata.name: Departure Within Shattered Windmills #218
metadata.description:
I wrote the following when reviewing the outputs...

The wind is gone,
My windmill falls,
I reach out to catch the pieces.
Half fall in my right hand,
The others in my left,
Two stacks of colored paper.
I’m holding my windmill,
I feel the breeze in my hair.
Each hand is empty,
My windmill rises,
I can see the wind.

'Departure Within Shattered Windmills' was originally inspired by suprematism, and then started to gain more complexity. It is still a combination of simple features, subdivided quads drawn on different planes of perspective. Chaos simulated by many organized grids. Countless pieces of a windmill.

25% of the royalties for each edition will pass to the original minter.

Each output is generated from code written in p5js.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: Cheerful Obscure #99
metadata.description:
"Cheerful Obscure" is the 26th project I have minted on fxhash. For this project, I experimented with filling all the shapes with gradients. This is a gradient, that is a gradient, gradients everywhere!

Built on top of FX(STDIO)

processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes

- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (11x14" @ 150 dpi)

metadata.name: Lost in the attraction / abstraction #68
metadata.description:
This project is an experiment with a chaotic attractor, radial symmetry and some Perlin noise.

---
Features

Parts: the number of symmetrical parts (4|6|8|10)

Palette: the palette chosen to draw the sketch

Attractors incrementation: a number between 0.0013 and 0.003 which will increment the parameters (a, b, c & d) of an attractor (Clifford A. Pickover).

---
Resolutions & controls

By default the work is drawn on a canvas of 1280 x 1280 pixels but you can double or triple this resolution, for this in live mode add to the URL &scale= with the desired factor.

You can also download an image (PNG) by pressing [d] key.


---
This artwork celebrate the first anniversary of FxHash, 50% of the proceeds will go to the Processing Foundation.


Created with typescript and simplex-noise (npm package). 

Artwork by Nicolas Lebrun / @nclslbn / https://nicolas-lebrun.fr/contact/
